  "texts": [
    "(4.30)We can also derive another expression more directly.",
    "We start with an infinite product formII 4d USp(2N) N II 4d USp(∞) N = ∞ k=N +1 (q k t -4k; q) ∞ (q k+ 1 2 t -4k+2; q) ∞ = ∞ m=1 (x 2N +2m; q) ∞ (x 2N +2m y; q) ∞ (4.31) = ∞ m=1 ∞ ℓ=0 1 -zx 2m q ℓ 1 -zx 2m yq ℓ.",
    "(4.32) JHEP12(2024)227This form itself is not useful to compute the giant graviton expansion.",
    "We rewrite it as follows.logII 4d USp(2N) N II 4d USp(∞) N = ∞ m=1 ∞ ℓ=0 log 1 -zx 2m q ℓ 1 -zx 2m yq ℓ (4.33) = ∞ m=1 ∞ ℓ=0 ∞ n=1 z n n (x 2mn y n q ℓn -x 2mn q ℓn) (4.34) = - ∞ n=1 z n x 2n (1 -y n) n(1 -x 2n)(1 -q n).",
    "(4.35)Therefore we find∞ k=0 z k fk (x, y; q) = exp - ∞ n=1 z n x 2n (1 -y n) n(1 -x 2n)(1 -q n) = ∞ n=0 ∞ m=0 1 -x 2n+2 q m z 1 -yx 2n+2 q m z."
